The '''Cincinnati Subway''' is a set of incomplete, derelict [[tunnel]]s and stations for a [[rapid transit]] system beneath the streets of [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]]. Although it is only a little over 2 miles in length, it is the largest abandoned subway tunnel system in the [[United States]]. Construction began in the early 1900s as an upgrade to the [[Streetcars in Cincinnati|Cincinnati streetcar system]], but was abandoned due to escalating costs, the collapse of funding amidst political bickering, and the [[Great Depression]] during the 1920s and 1930s.

In 1928, the construction of the subway system in Cincinnati was indefinitely canceled. There are no plans to revive the project.

==History==
Rapid transit was seen as the solution for downtown congestion during the first quarter of the 20th century. Six million dollars were allocated for the project, but construction was delayed due to [[World War I]]. Unexpected post-war inflation doubled the cost of construction, so the project could not be finished at the original estimated price.

Various attempts to use the subway tunnels for mass transit have been unsuccessful. Political squabbling, the Great Depression, [[World War II]], and the rise in popularity of the [[automobile]] have contributed to the failure of the proposals.<ref name="2003_radel_article">{{cite news|last=Radel|first=Cliff|title=Life under the city: Subway legend has never left the station|pages=12–27|newspaper=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=May 24, 2003|url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2003/05/24/loc_radel24.html|accessdate=2008-06-08}}</ref> Today, many Cincinnatians are unaware of the tunnels underneath them.<ref name="city_of_cincinnati_the_cincinnati_subway">{{Cite news|title=City of Cincinnati&nbsp;— The Cincinnati Subway |accessdate=2008-12-07 |url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/transeng/pages/-7185-/ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430170135/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/transeng/pages/-7185-/ |archivedate=April 30, 2008 }}</ref>

===Context===
[[File:Cincinnati-canal-map.png|thumb|Former location of the [[Miami and Erie Canal]] in downtown Cincinnati. ]]
From 1825 to 1920 the [[Miami and Erie Canal]] divided Cincinnati's residential neighborhood of [[Over-the-Rhine]] from the business district of downtown.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|17}}<ref name="April_3_1926_Enquirer">{{Cite news|last=Body in Charge of Transit System|title=Progress of Work Reviewed|newspaper=Cincinnati Enquirer|pages=14–15|date=April 3, 1926|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The canal was used to transport goods and people from the [[Great Lakes]] to the [[Ohio River]] and subsequently the [[Mississippi River]] via Cincinnati, until the popularity of railroads caused it to become disused.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=17}} The canal became unprofitable by 1856{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=17}} and was abandoned by the city in 1877.<ref name="2003_radel_article" />

On September 15, 1883 a weekly Cincinnati magazine called ''The Graphic'' proposed that the "dead old ditch" be used to provide an unobstructed route for a subway system, with a large boulevard above.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=18}} 

In 1888, Cincinnati began adopting electric streetcars{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=18}}, which soon became the main form of public transportation.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=19}} During this period Cincinnati was one of the seven most populous US cities<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|17}}and had a rate of growth and economic importance that was similar to that of [[New York City]] and [[Chicago]].<ref name="2003_radel_article" /> The slow streetcars shared the crowded streets with horse-drawn carriages and people, and collided with the first automobiles on an almost daily basis.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|19}} It was not unusual for trips between downtown and the surrounding suburbs to take 45 minutes to an hour.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|46}} Despite having {{convert|222|mi|km}} of streetcar tracks, the city found itself in a growing traffic nightmare.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|19}}

Another newspaper, the ''Cincinnati Commercial Tribune'', gave encouraging words to the public and said "We believe that the city we love, our home, is at the turning point, and that with the coming of Rapid Transit we will have the beginning of a Greater, More Prosperous, Healthier and Happier Cincinnati. We believe that a Vote for the Loop is a Vote for the best interests of all of us, and it is with pride that we state that every newspaper in the city is for the Loop, and practically all of the Business organizations as well as the Trades Unions." This helped the project win the fight in the polls when the people of Cincinnati enthusiastically passed bill to start construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/10/12411632/public-transportation-failures-america-cincinnati-subway|title=The secret history of Cincinnati's ghost subway|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref>

===Planning===
In 1910, [[Henry Thomas Hunt]] spearheaded plans for a new rapid transit system.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=35}} The next year City Council convinced the [[Ohio State Legislature]] to lease the city's portion of the canal for use as a boulevard and subway system.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=17}} The city hired experts that worked on Boston's and Chicago's rapid transit systems to research the best possible implementation for Cincinnati's rapid transit system.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=36}} The result were four "Schemes," or proposed routes. The chosen plan—Scheme IV, modification H—looped around the city hitting the central suburbs of [[St. Bernard, Ohio|St. Bernard]] and [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]], the eastern suburbs of [[Oakley, Ohio|Oakley]] and [[Hyde Park, Ohio|Hyde Park]], and then returned into downtown.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=36}}

In 1916 City Council authorized a bond issue of $6 million with an interest rate of 4.25 percent,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|title=... Bonds To Pay 4{{fraction|1|4}}% Interest |newspaper=[[Cincinnati Post]] |page=12 |date=June 17, 1916 |postscript=<!--None--> }}</ref>{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} and then held a plebiscite on the rapid transit plan.<ref name="April_3_1926_Enquirer" /> The bond was supposed to fund a {{convert|16|mi|km}} subway system stretching across Cincinnati, which would, in turn, slow or even stop the decline of Cincinnati's population at the time. One advertisement in support of the subway proclaimed, "Every newspaper in the city is for the Loop, and practically all of the Business organizations as well as the Trades Unions."{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} On April 17, 1917, Cincinnati citizens voted in favor of using the bond for a Rapid Transit system, 30,165 to 14,286.<ref name="April_3_1926_Enquirer" /> The system would be built as an [[elevated railway]] through downtown, [[Evanston, Cincinnati|Evanston]], [[Oakley, Cincinnati|Oakley]], and [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]], with an underground portion to be built under the [[Miami and Erie Canal]] and extend under the [[Mill Creek (Ohio)|Mill Creek]] valley to [[St. Bernard, Ohio|St. Bernard]].{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

However, because the United States entered [[World War I]] just 11 days earlier,<ref name="2003_radel_article" /> construction was halted because no capital issues of bonds were permitted during the war.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}<ref name="April_3_1926_Enquirer" />{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=45}}

{{Quote|War conditions have prompted the opinion in certain official quarters that it would be unwise to proceed with the construction of the loop until after the war. High costs of materials and the difficulty in obtaining deliveries are cited as arguments in favor of the temporary abandonment of the project.|''[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]'', "Subway Again May Meet Delay: Postponement Of Plans Until After War Is Considered," April 5, 1918 (p. 9)}}

===Construction and failure===
When the war ended in 1918, costs had increased. By 1919 the cost of construction had doubled,<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|71}} increasing the original price to complete the loop from $12 million to $13 million.<ref name="April_3_1926_Enquirer" /> Regardless, the city began work on January 28, 1920,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forgottenoh.com/subway.html|title=The Cincinnati Subway System|work=Ohio Exploration|accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> at the current intersection of Walnut Street and Central Parkway,{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} and the city planned to raise the money to complete the loop later, since funds were so low and there was a shortage in construction materials. The subway's construction caused the foundations of buildings along the route to crack, leading to much litigation against the subway.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} When bonds ran out in 1927, construction ended with {{convert|7|mi|km|0|spell=in}} of subway dug or graded, but no track had been laid.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}
[[File:Cincinnati Subway Entrance 01 2005 10 22.JPG|thumb|A station platform and unlaid trackbed.|left]]New estimates to complete the loop ranged from an additional $6 million to $12 million.<ref name="2003_radel_article" /> The eastern part of the loop was later canceled as a cost-cutting measure.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} The boulevard that ran on top of the subway, Central Parkway, officially opened to traffic on October 1, 1928, and was followed by a week of public celebration.<ref name="singer">{{cite book|last=Singer|first=Allen J.|title=The Cincinnati subway: history of rapid transit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7F8zr3DwTsC|accessdate=July 23, 2011|series=Images of America Series|date=May 26, 2003|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|location=Mount Pleasant, SC|isbn=978-0-7385-2314-9}}</ref>{{rp|47}} However, by the late 1920s, [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] had severely impacted the city, because alcoholic beverages, a major source of revenue for the city, were not allowed to be purchased.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} Still, as late as 1926–1927, new tunnels, such as the Hopple Street Tunnel, were being built.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

Once it became apparent that the original rapid transit plan had failed, political infighting in City Hall stalled any new progress,<ref name="2003_radel_article" /><ref name="singer"/>{{rp|73}} due to an anti-City Hall campaign led by city manager [[Murray Seasongood]] beginning in 1920.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} Newspapers started to print articles arguing against the subway, using such rationales as the tight curve of the subway and its small tunnels to try to advocate against its completion. 

Along with this, the cities of Norwood and Saint Bernard continuously negotiated with the city of Cincinnati, pushing the construction back another year. Two more months were piled on to the delay also Brighton residents were upset with the blast damages destroying their property. The construction methods created suspicion to state examiners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/dote/about-transportation-engineering/historical-information/the-cincinnati-subway/|title=The Cincinnati Subway|website=www.cincinnati-oh.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>

In January 1929, Seasongood &ndash; by then the Mayor &ndash; discontinued the Rapid Transit Commission, which until then had been in control of the subway's construction; that year, his own office took control of the project.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} Any hope of raising the money to complete the subway was further delayed with the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|stock market crash of 1929]].<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|81}} Though few citizens owned automobiles when Mayor Hunt first planned rapid transit in 1910, their increasing popularity and convenience helped fuel critics' arguments against a subway system. They began referring to the project as "Cincinnati's [[White Elephant]]."<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|71, 81}} Even so, the "temporary" hiatus on construction was expected to end after the economy got better, and many Cincinnatians, including Seasongood, hoped that the subway would finally be completed.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

===Attempts at revival===
There have been many attempts to complete the tunnels, but few people know why the subway was never completed or used for another significant purpose.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} In 1936 the city commissioned the Engineers' Club of Cincinnati to produce a report on how to use the unfinished rapid transit property.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|82}} The report could not find any use for the tunnels other than what they had been designed for. Because the city's needs had changed from twenty years earlier, the report suggested that the subway "should be forgotten".<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|82}} In 1939 the tunnels were researched for possible automobile traffic, but were found to be unsuitable for that use.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|82}} In 1940 the city sought the advice of several experts to settle once and for all the fate of the subway. The report recommended placing all streetcar and trolley transportation underground (i.e., a subway), but Cincinnati already had too many other expensive public projects underway. In any case, the plan was put on hold yet again when the United States entered World War II in 1941.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|82, 92}}

During World War II, the city was focused on war-time rationing, so completing the subway was not a high priority.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|82}} The tunnels were suggested as possible air raid shelters, but the idea was never implemented.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|92}} Underground storage of commercial and military supplies was also proposed as a use for the tunnels, or as a pathway to bring freight into the heart of the city, but both ideas were rejected because they would delay bringing mass transit to Cincinnati.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|92}} After the war ended the City Planning Commission decided to not include the subway in its plans. Instead, the commission would use the loop's right-of-way as pathways for [[Interstate 75 in Ohio|Interstate 75]] and the [[Ohio State Route 562|Norwood Lateral]].<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|98,103}} Then, in the 1950s, a massive {{convert|52|in|m|adj=on}}<ref name="modern_subway_options">{{Cite news|title=Cincinnati Considers Options For Decades-Old Unfinished Subway|accessdate=2008-05-12|url=http://www.wlwt.com/news/14790068/detail.html|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524084219/http://www.wlwt.com/news/14790068/detail.html|archivedate=2011-05-24|df=}}</ref> [[water main]] was laid in the northbound tunnel to save $300,000<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|102}} by not digging a new tunnel for the water main.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} According to the engineering firm [[Parsons Brinckerhoff]], a redundant water main was installed during the construction of [[Fort Washington Way]] so the water main in the subway could be removed easily.<ref name="2002_7_29_pilcher_article">{{cite news|last=Pilcher|first=James|title=Abandoned subway could save light rail plan|newspaper=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=July 29, 2002|url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2002/07/29/loc_abandoned_subway.html|accessdate=2008-07-03}}</ref> There is also an escape clause in Ordinance No. 154-1956 that states, "in the event said section of the rapid transit subway is, at some future date, needed for rapid transit purposes, the Water Works shall remove said main at its sole cost."<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|102}}

In the 1960's the Hamilton county proposed the Liberty Street station be turned into a bomb shelter.  However, the result was a very weak attempt at a fallout shelter that would not provide much for those residing in it. There were also suggestions by investors to turn the tunnels into passages for freight trains, but that project failed due to the sharp turns existing in the tunnels that freight trains could not handle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-transit.net|title=Cincinnati-Transit.net|website=www.cincinnati-transit.net|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>

The subway bonds were paid off in 1966 at a total cost of $13,019,982.45.<ref name="2003_radel_article" /> Around that time Meier's Wine Cellars Inc. wanted to use the subway tunnels to store wine, as well as install a bottling operation to draw tourists, but it fell through due to a lack of proper building codes.<ref name="singer"/>{{rp|110}} In the 1970s [[Nick Clooney]] wanted to turn parts of the tunnel into an underground mall and a night club, but that fell through early on due to insurance issues.<ref name="New_life_for_old_subway">Krewedl, Derek. (October 22, 2002) "New life for old subway?", Downtowner. pp.1,14.</ref>{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=110}} In the 1980s the city pitched the tunnels to [[Hollywood]] filmmakers as a location to shoot subway scenes.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=110}} In particular, the location was presented to the makers of ''[[Batman Forever]]'', but as of 2008 the tunnels had not been used in any feature films.{{sfnp|Singer|2003|p=110}}

In 2002, a regional [[light rail]] system was proposed to use the tunnels;{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} the system would cost $2.6 billion and take thirty years to build.<ref name="2002_7_29_pilcher_article" /> The tunnels were favored because they were in an ideal location, they could easily be used to connect the east side and the west sides of Cincinnati, and they would have saved the city at least $100 million in construction costs at the time.<ref name="2002_7_29_pilcher_article" /> The light rail plan, called [[MetroMoves]], proposed a tax levy that would have raised sales tax in Hamilton county by a half-cent.<ref name="2002_10_6_pilcher_article">{{cite news|last=Pilcher|first=James|title=Metro plan hits wall of resistance|newspaper=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=November 6, 2002|url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2002/11/06/loc_literail06.html|accessdate=2008-07-03}}</ref>{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} The plan was voted down by more than a 2-to-1 ratio,<ref name="2002_10_6_pilcher_article" /> with 68% opposing MetroMoves.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} Still, an underground portion of the [[Riverfront Transit Center]] was built to serve the proposed, unbuilt MetroMoves lines; this transit center was later served by another Cincinnati streetcar line, the [[Cincinnati Streetcar]].{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

==Current status==
The uncompleted subway tunnels and stations have been described as "in good shape."<ref name="2002_7_29_pilcher_article" /> This is partially credited to the original construction quality,<ref name="New_life_for_old_subway" /> and partially because Cincinnati needs to maintain the tunnel, using tax revenues, due to the presence of Central Parkway on top of it.<ref name="modern_subway_options" /><ref name="2002_7_29_pilcher_article" />

In 2008 it was estimated that it would cost $2.6 million to simply keep maintaining the tunnels, $19 million to fill the tunnels with dirt, and $100.5 million to revive the tunnels for modern subway use.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}} Relocating the {{convert|52|in|m|adj=on}} water main would cost $14 million.<ref name="modern_subway_options" /> {{As of|2016|08|alt=As of August 2016}}, the abandoned tunnel is used to carry the relocated water main and some [[optical fiber cable]]s.{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

The abandoned tunnels are frequented by [[urban exploration|urban explorers]] and the [[homelessness in the United States|homeless]].{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}

===Stations and route===
[[File:Cincinnati subway tunnel door.jpg|thumb|This tunnel entrance near the Western Hills Viaduct is clearly visible from [[Interstate 75 in Ohio|Interstate 75]].]]
Seven stations were completed along Central Parkway: four underground and three above ground. The underground stations remain intact{{sfnp|Hawkins|2016}}, but the above-ground stations were demolished when [[Interstate 75 in Ohio|I-75]] was built in the 1960s. The underground stations' locations are at Race Street, Liberty Street, Linn Street, and Brighton Place, while the above-ground stations' locations were at Marshall Street, Ludlow Avenue, Clifton Avenue, and Reading Road

The first station was the Race Street Station, which was to serve as the main hub. It was configured with the [[Island platform|platform in the center]], with the subway running along the north and south side. Next was Liberty Street, which was a through-station. It was a simple design with a platform on each side of the track. Third was Linn Street, also a through station. Laid out similarly to Liberty Street, this station has been sealed up, and can be easily missed when walking through. Fourth was Brighton Place, another through-station.

Marshall Street was the most grand of the above-ground stations, located to the west near the Mill Creek Valley. Ludlow Avenue Station was constructed under the south side of the Ludlow Viaduct and was also a through-station. The last to be completed was Clifton Avenue, which was located where the street passes under present day I-75. There were additional stations in the plan; however, funding ran out as the project reached [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]].<ref name="subway_movie_2010">''[http://www.thecincinnatisubway.com Cincinnati's Abandoned Subway]'', (2010). Pro. Paige E. Malott. Dir. Leland Schuler. DVD. Time Bonus Productions, LLC, Cincinnati, OH.</ref>

===Engineering===
The subway tunnels run north and south. Each of the two halves of the tube has a minimum width of {{convert|13|ft|m}} and a height of {{convert|15|ft|6|in|m}}. Each tunnel has parallel wooden stringers which are bolted to the floor, and are intended to support steel rails that were never laid. They are {{convert|59|in|m}} from center to center, which is {{convert|6|in}}  wider than most railway lines. All curves in the tunnel are gradual, and on those curves [[Cant (road/rail)|the outside stringer was raised higher than the inner stringer]] to accommodate trains traveling at speeds of more than {{convert|40|mph}}.<ref name="april_24_1936_times_star">{{Cite news|last=Stimson|first=George P.|title=Unused Subway System is in Almost Perfect Condition|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Times-Star]]|page=2|date=April 24, 1936|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>

There were many details of the unfinished subway system, such as a provision for a station at Mohawk Corner, where the wall has been set back. At Walnut Street the lines begin to curve south to go into downtown, but they are stopped short by a bricked up wall. The subway tunnel is double-tracked throughout its entire length, with a concrete wall separating the two tracks. Openings in the wall enable persons to step from one track to another. The tunnels are well ventilated and provide much light until Liberty Street is reached.<ref name="april_24_1936_times_star"/>

