[[File:Toini Gustafsson Rönnlund in Jan 2014.jpg|thumb|right|[[Toini Gustafsson]] of Sweden won three medals in cross-country skiing in Grenoble.|alt=A woman, standing, wearing a green necklace.]]
The [[1968 Winter Olympics]], officially known as the ''X Olympic Winter Games'', was a winter [[multi-sport event]] held in [[Grenoble]], France, from 6 to 18 February 1968. A total of 1,158 athletes representing 37 [[National Olympic Committee]]s (NOCs) participated in 35 events from 10 different [[Olympic sports#Winter Olympics|sports and disciplines]].<ref name="IOC">{{cite web|title=Grenoble 1968 Winter Olympics|url=http://www.olympic.org/en/content/Olympic-Games/All-Past-Olympic-Games/Winter/Grenoble-1968/|work=Olympic.org|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=13 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106094950/http://www.olympic.org/en/content/Olympic-Games/All-Past-Olympic-Games/Winter/Grenoble-1968|archivedate=6 November 2015|df=}}</ref>  The Olympic programme was largely unchanged from four years prior [[1964 Winter Olympics|in Innsbruck]]; one event was added, a [[Biathlon at the 1968 Winter Olympics – Relay|relay event]] in [[Biathlon at the 1968 Winter Olympics|biathlon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1968/BIA/mens-4-x-7_5-kilometres-relay.html|title=Biathlon at the 1968 Grenoble Winter Games: Men's 4 x 7.5 kilometres Relay|last=Kubatko|first=Justin|work=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=13 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414172456/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1968/BIA/mens-4-x-7_5-kilometres-relay.html|archivedate=14 April 2018|df=}}</ref>

[[Norway at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Norway]] won the most medals, with 14, and the most gold medals with 6.The [[Soviet Union at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Soviet Union]] finished second in both tallies, with 5 golds and 13 medals in total.<ref name="SR" />  Of the 37 NOCs to participate at Grenoble, 15 won at least one medal, with 13 of those winning at least one gold medal.<ref name="SR" />  [[East Germany at the 1968 Winter Olympics|East]] and [[West Germany at the 1968 Winter Olympics|West Germany]] entered separate teams for the first time, having [[United Team of Germany|competed together]] in the three prior Winter Olympics.  Both nations won gold medals, their first competing as different nations.<ref>{{cite web|title=1968 Grenoble, France|url=http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/history/story/2009/11/26/sp-1968-grenoble.html|work=Vancouver Now|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|accessdate=14 April 2018|date=18 December 2009|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625001718/http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/history/story/2009/11/26/sp-1968-grenoble.html|archivedate=25 June 2012|df=}}</ref>  [[Czechoslovakia at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Czechoslovakia]] won its first gold Winter Olympics medal, achieved by [[Jiří Raška]] in the [[Ski jumping at the 1968 Winter Olympics – Normal hill individual|ski jumping normal hill]] event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/TCH/|title=Czechoslovakia|last=Kubatko|first=Justin|work=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=13 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618021315/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/TCH/|archivedate=18 June 2010|df=}}</ref>   [[Romania at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Romania]] won its first, and as of the [[2018 Winter Olympics]], only medal in a Winter Olympics in the [[Bobsleigh at the 1968 Winter Olympics – Two-man|two-man bobsleigh]] event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/panturu-and-neagoe-make-winter-games-history-for-romania|title=Panțuru and Neagoe make Winter Games history for Romania|date=15 February 1968|publisher=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=14 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325041716/https://www.olympic.org/news/panturu-and-neagoe-make-winter-games-history-for-romania|archivedate=25 March 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/ROU/|title=Romania|last=Kubatko|first=Justin|work=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=13 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415124804/https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/ROU/|archivedate=15 April 2018|df=}}</ref>

[[Jean-Claude Killy]] of [[France at the 1968 Winter Olympics|France]] was the most successful athlete at these games, winning all three of the men's [[Alpine skiing at the 1968 Winter Olympics|alpine skiing]] events.  Two other athletes each won three medals: [[Sweden at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Sweden's]] [[Toini Gustafsson]] earned two golds and a silver, and [[Finland at the 1968 Winter Olympics|Finland's]] [[Eero Mäntyranta]] won a silver and two bronzes. Both of them were competitors in [[Cross-country skiing at the 1968 Winter Olympics|cross-country skiing]].  Four other athletes—[[Luciano de Paolis]], [[Ole Ellefsæter]], [[Harald Grønningen]], and [[Eugenio Monti]]—won two gold medals, and 29 individuals in total won at least two medals in Grenoble.<ref name="SR" />  In [[Speed skating at the 1968 Winter Olympics|speed skating]], three different events ended with ties for the silver medal position, one, the [[Speed skating at the 1968 Winter Olympics – Women's 500 metres|women's 500 metres]] ended in a three-way tie for silver.<ref name="SSWomen's500" />  In all three cases, multiple silver medals and no bronze medals were awarded.<ref name="SSMen's500" /><ref name="SSMen's1500" />  In [[Figure skating at the 1968 Winter Olympics|figure skating]], American [[Peggy Flemming]] won the gold medal in ladies' singles; this came a mere seven years after the 1961 crash of [[Sabena Flight 548]] that killed the entire US figure skating team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/1968-peggy-fleming-takes-home-only-us-gold-medal-grenoble|title=1968: Peggy Fleming takes home only U.S. gold medal from Grenoble|last=Lutz|first=Rachel|date=1 February 2018|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=25 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426080927/http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/1968-peggy-fleming-takes-home-only-us-gold-medal-grenoble#|archive-date=2018-04-26|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

