A '''lithotope''' is either an [[natural environment|environment]] in which a [[sediment]] was deposited or an area of uniform [[sedimentation]].


1. Surface or area of uniform precipitation.
 2. Breed, sediment or solid sediment, having a relatively homogeneous or resistant sedimentation environment.
[[Category:Sedimentology]]
[[Category:Environments]]


{{Geology-stub}}

'''Ras Rakan''' ({{lang-ar|رأس راكان}}) is the northernmost point in the [[Qatar|Qatari Peninsula]], located in [[Al Shamal]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bird|first=Eric|title=Encyclopedia of the World's Coastal Landforms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mfo5TPb7SDsC&pg=PA1038|publisher=Springer|year=2010|page=1038|isbn=978-1402086380}}</ref> It is the north-western point of an islet called Jazirat Ras Rakan, but as the channel between this islet and the mainland is not passable for boats, Jazirat Ras Rakan may be regarded as forming the northern extremity of the promontory.<ref name="qdl">{{cite web|url=http://www.qdl.qa/en/archive/81055/vdc_100023727635.0x000023|title='Gazetteer of Arabia Vol. II' [1557] (636/688)|publisher=Qatar Digital Library|year=1917|accessdate=31 December 2015}} ''This article incorporates text from this source, which is in the [[public domain]].''</ref>
==Location== The islet is nearly 1 ½ miles from the shore, and may be reached by wading through low water. The northernmost town of Qatar, [[Ar Ru'ays]], lies 2 ½ miles south-east from the islet.<ref name="qdl"/> If approached at from a northward direction, Ar Ru'ays becomes visible before Ras Rakan is spotted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qdl.qa/en/archive/81055/vdc_100023623199.0x000046|title=‘Persian Gulf pilot comprising the Persian Gulf and its approaches from Ras al Hadd, in the south-west, to Cape Monze, in the east.’ [132v] (269/404)|publisher=Qatar Digital Library|year=1932|accessdate=31 December 2015}} ''This article incorporates text from this source, which is in the [[public domain]].''</ref>
==Description== Jazirat Ras Rakkan is a very low, T-shaped islet, with tufts of grass on it.<ref name="qdl"/> There are some small mangroves on the southern side of it.<ref>{{cite book|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=The Persian Gulf pilot: comprising the Persian Gulf, Gulf of Omán; and Makran coast|publisher=Hydrographic Dept|location=Great Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m5ItAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA127|page=127|year=1890}}</ref> It is nearly 2 miles in length east to west, and extremely narrow. The T-head, at its western end, is 1 mile long.<ref name="qdl"/>
==References== {{reflist}}
{{coord|26|11|1|N|51|12|56|E|display=title|region:QA_type:city_source:wikimapia}}
[[Category:Al Shamal]] [[Category:Geography of Qatar]] [[Category:Islands of Qatar]]
{{Qatar-geo-stub}}

The '''Royal Danish Geographical Society''' ('''RDGS''', {{lang-da|Det Kongelige Danske Geografiske Selskab}}) is a [[scientific society]] aimed at furthering the knowledge of the [[Earth]] and its inhabitants and to disseminate interest in the science of [[geography]].
It was founded 18 November 1876 on the initiative of Professor E. D. Erslev. The society is based in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].
The society awards the [[Hans Egede Medal]] in silver 'preferably for geographical studies and researches in the Arctic countries'. It was established in 1916 and named after [[Hans Egede]], who was a Danish missionary in Greenland.
